 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Targeting of the correct audience. Linked very much to the previous point is the need to 
ensure that the correct audience is identified and that all the key information is then 
directed to this audience.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢User ownership. The fault of many an information system is to impose information on individuals without first including them in the process of identifying and determining 
information requirements. This can be very demotivating. It is a very valid step to 
include potential users at the systems design stage, thus conferring user ownership of 
the information when the system is in place. The information should be useful, and 
those who use the information should understand the detail.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Reactivity to changes in business activity. Not a simple requirement to put into practice, but an effective control system will need to be dynamic and so take account of any changes 
in business activity. To a certain extent this is achieved through flexible budgeting.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Timeliness. Reports must be available at the agreed time, and the frequency of reports 
should be such that suitable control action can be taken.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Ease of maintenance. A fairly obvious comment is that an effective system must not be overly complicated to maintain and progress. Simplicity is certainly a virtue.Cost and Performance Monitoring 519
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Cost-effectiveness. Again, a fairly obvious but very relevant point is that a monitoring 
system should not cost more to set up and run than can possibly be saved through 
using the system.
The elements of good practice that come under the category of content have almost all been 
covered in previous sections, and they are as follows:
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ the need for clear cost categories, with careful identification of fixed and variable costs;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ the use of flexible budgeting;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ the use of variance analysis;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ the clarification of controllable and non-controllable elements;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ the use of reference points against which the monitored elements can be measured Ã¢â‚¬â€œ 
these might include:
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ budget;
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ forecast;
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ trends;
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ targets;
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ comparative league tables.
(The final two factors are useful for monitoring contractor operations and for setting up inter-site comparisons.)
The final aspect of good practice concerns the type of output that the system produces. This is 
the information on which any form of action is based. It has already been emphasized that this information must be relevant and useful. The major output characteristics are:
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Reports can vary. They may be:
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ summary (providing key statistics only);
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ exception (identifying the major deviations from plan);
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ detailed (including all information).
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Reports should be made to a standard format Ã¢â‚¬â€œ especially important where any inter-site comparisons are to be made.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Data should be presented in whatever means is most appropriate to the eventual use of the data.
Different types of data output are as follows:
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢trend data Ã¢â‚¬â€œ based upon moving annual totals to identify long-term changes;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢comparative data:
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ data analysis over a short period (eg this month against last month),
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ data analysed against a target (eg this month compared with budget),
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ data analysed against a measured standard  (eg this month compared with standard),
 Ã¢â‚¬â€œ comparative data analysis also identifies variances that indicate the degree of 
performance success;520 operational Management
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢indices Ã¢â‚¬â€œ data in statistical form compared with a base position over time;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ratio Ã¢â‚¬â€œ a combination of two or more pieces of meaningful data to form a useful figure 
for comparison;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢graphs Ã¢â‚¬â€œ comparative trends in pictorial form.
What do companies see as being the most valuable characteristics of a good monitoring 
system? The example outlined below provides an indication:
An international manufacturer and supplier of computer equipment identified the need for 
a more adequate information system for monitoring and controlling performance in its 
three warehouses. The company set up a project team to investigate these requirements, 
and produced some interesting output.
Five key areas for measurement were identified:
1. Volume Ã¢â‚¬â€œ what is moving through the warehouse?
2. Efficiency Ã¢â‚¬â€œ how well is the operation being run?
3. Cost-effectiveness Ã¢â‚¬â€œ is the cost reflecting the work being undertaken?
4. Quality Ã¢â‚¬â€œ how well are the service levels being met?
5. Stability Ã¢â‚¬â€œ what does the staff turnover picture look like?
Outline requirements were:
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ overall business control;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ activity measures within the business area;
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ trend indicators and productivity measures.
Factors for consideration were:
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Action Ã¢â‚¬â€œ the system should lead to a change in the current position, and should 
be used.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Confusion Ã¢â‚¬â€œ the system should filter out the irrelevant information that confuses and diverts attention.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Comprehensibility Ã¢â‚¬â€œ everyone who receives information must understand it.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Defensiveness Ã¢â‚¬â€œ a defensive reaction to figures, especially adverse ones, needs to be overcome.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Timeliness Ã¢â‚¬â€œ the information has to be available in sufficient time for action to be taken.Cost and Performance Monitoring 521
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Validity Ã¢â‚¬â€œ actual changes in performance must be reflected by the system.
 Ã¢â‚¬Â¢Dynamism  Ã¢â‚¬â€œ the system must be sensitive to the changing internal and external conditions, 
as tomorrowÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s problems cannot be solved with yesterdayÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s measurement system.
